definition.value: A methoxycinnamic acid with three methoxy substituents at the 3-, 4- and 5-positions.
A 1,3-benzoxathiole having a hydroxy substituent at the 6-position.
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
Dicarboxylate anion of trans-2,3-epoxysuccinic acid.
A fatty acid anion with a chain length of C13 or greater.
The conjugate base of 5-oxoproline.
The conjugate base of a 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound formed by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
The carboxylate anion of N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosylceramide.
A carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any N-acylglycine.
The conjugate base of trans-caffeic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from cyclotriphosphoric acid.; major species at pH 7.3.
The carboxylate anion of a 1,2-diacyl-3-[3-(alpha-D-N-acetylneuraminyl)-beta-D-galactosyl]-sn-glycerol.
Conjugate base of N-benzoyl-4-hydroxyanthranilic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The ammonium betaine of a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-methoxy-4-hydroxy-5-all-trans-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 6 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero 3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group at position 1 is unspecified while that at position 2 is specified as (S)-12-hydroxyoleoyl.
Trianion of 3-phosphoglyceric acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of D-glutamine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A  dihydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of cis-caffeic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A carbohydrate acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-dehydro-D-gluconic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
The ammonium betaine of a 1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH; major species at pH 7.3.
A N-alkylpiperazine that is piperzine in which the nitrogens atoms are substituted by 2-(2-hydroxyethoxy)ethyl and (4-chlorophenyl)(phenyl)methyl groups respectively.
The ionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the carboxy groups of alginic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion arising from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 2-hydroxy-3-oxosuccinic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The ammonium betaine formed from 1-acyl-2-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion where the hydroxy group is placed at position 2 (alpha to the carboxy group) and has (R)-stereochemistry; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid betaine obtaine by exhaustive methylation of the alpha-amino group of L-tryptophan with concomitant deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 3,4-dihydroxy-5-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 6 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of trimethylamine, obtained via protonation of the nitrogen; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of isopenicillin N.
Conjugate base of penicillin N.
An icosapentaenoate that is the conjugate base of all-cis-5,8,11,14,17-icosapentaenoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
Dianionic form of selenophosphoric acid.
Conjugate base of 2,3-dihydroxy-trans-cinnamic acid.
A carbohydrate acid anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-D-galacturonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-acetyl-beta-neuraminic acid.
Conjugate base of threo-3-methyl-L-aspartic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminic acid.
Dicarboxylate anion arising from deprotonation of both carboxylic acid groups of iminoaspartic acid.
The conjugate base of a 2-hydroxy carboxylic acid.
The carboxylate anion formed from an alpha-D-glucosiduronic acid
An organic phosphoric acid derivative in which one or more oxygen atoms of the phosphate group(s) has been deprotonated.
